node.text:
Hey hi!
I wanted to share with you this song by my friends @sophiesofree and @r_a_i_o called Cunaq. You can find it in the Spotify link in my linktree if you click “What’s on my playlist”. I can’t get enough of it at the moment, her voice is so beautiful, it’s like a crystal singing bowl to me. 

I asked Sophie about the meaning, she said:

“It’s a song of praise and prayer to the Waters, which bring us purification and renewal. We shed our tears in order to see the world afresh, in joy and celebration. It’s Based on a traditional Peruvian water song” 
. 
I hope this song makes you flow, or purifies a little something something from your layers. 
.
I’m loving you from this moist chilly jungly cabin where I’m here wearing pants. Yes pants. And hoping you out there are taking gentle breaks from your devices to frolic around nonsensically making jokes with loved ones that are so not funny they are the funniest
. 
And, if you have seen any interesting, informative, controversial, moving, educational documentaries lately? Please do tell
. 
love and yum
Meghan 
.

node.text:
The light peeks out amplifying everything that’s been cleansed with the overwhelming smells of renewal.

There are times in our lives that feel like walking alone up an alligator inhabited shit stream on spiky stones in a lightening storm during an earthquake in the dark. Inner navigation sometimes leads us through these kinds of chasms and rational thought equates it to a mistake or wrong turn in the road. 

We can be wise and practice lots and do all the things and still get lost. And lost again. 

To get lost, feel confused, fall face first in a dung pile and lose your shoes can be a good sign. Maybe not a sign we can see at the time, but we all know what it’s like when the river turns clear, the sun peaks out from the clouds, we find our shoes and the lessons become crystallized in our blood.

But what to do when the storm is thick with no end in sight and the feels are terrorizing. 

One question I have been asking myself lately is: what does it look/feel like to approach this situation/relationship/shit storm/conflict- GRACEFULLY?

When I’m in the middle of a storm, asking this question does not suddenly clear the clouds, but it generates some tiny shifts in the way I realize my own resistance to the reality of my current situation. 

I’m nerding deep on the word GRACE this month as it’s the theme for studies in my online studio. 
What comes when I cozy up to this word is some kind of warm and soft, gentle but strong, sweet and beautiful presence. And when I try to apply this presence to my circumstance it teaches me allowance and gentle yielding to whatever the moment is washing over me. I remember with my body that grace is kindness to myself and the situation, whatever it may be. And when I really connect to the essence of the word grace, I’m taken to a beautiful core that resides in and through everything. 

Again, this does not clear the storm, nor does it mean that I’m suddenly in love with the situation or am taken over by feelings of peace and joy. But it imprints some wisdom somewhere and helps me let go of resistance, even just a little. 

I’m loving you from Bali and the bitches (aka-Lala, Dreamy, Soma) are sending sassy dirty-dog love too.

node.title: There are not many things in life like the feeling after a storm.

node.text:
Sometimes we have to fall out of balance to find balance. 

Sometimes the harder we fall, the better because those rocks at the bottom, when we hit them, don’t lie.  They knock the puzzle piece needed to see the lesson clearly, out of hiding. 
.
The Lessons in life that really stick rarely feel orgasmic and sometimes even ripping a bandaid off of a hairy spot can feel pleasurable in comparison. 
.
But the lessons like this, they stick stronger than superglue.  I’m learning a few of these at the moment.  It seems that any theme I create for my classes, I first must get spanked with.  It amazes me, often to tears of wft, how the lessons never stop. 

I’ve been frozen in some ways for the last month, but finally I feel some defrosting. This video is a slice of my yummy practice this am. Like coming home to the smell of curry on the stove yummy. It’s been a while since I’ve been able to self practice. Life had me occupied, stuck to a rocky bottom collecting old stones, but I’m happy to finally feel like I’m back. Needed to fall out of balance, um big time, to find a new way to stand.
.
How have you all been out there? Any spankings from hefty lessons lately? Missed you guys. Say hi pleaaaseeee 

Loving youuuu
Meghan

Hey!

Electric Booty is here!

The other day I posted a video of my little saucy quarantine fitness routine that I created for myself to complement my yoga practice. Today I’ve just posted one of these full routines to Youtube for you to try! (Click the linktr.ee in my bio to give it a try!) It’s a 30-minute sweaty strength training that is created to complement your yoga practices.

Electric Booty is the first of 5 classes from a complete home strength training program I made called Yoga Habit Sculptor. It’s all about toning and tuning parts of the body we use a lot in yoga to improve stamina, strength, flexibility, and posture. Each class has a strength element, as well as a stretch, little breath work, and mini-meditation. 

It squeezes in so many things I love into compact time and leaves me feeling perfectly worked, strong, saucy, and grounded. You can use ankle weights and dumbbells to spice up this exercise, or you can do it equipment-free!

Give it a try and let me know how it goes!

Love, 
Meghan

PS. If you like this routine, you can get access to the whole program, Yoga Habit Sculptor, (consisting of 5 strength classes and 1 bonus stretch class) by joining the Online Studio Membership.

node.text:
Thrusts of joy.  Haha this video is sped up so fast i hope you don’t get 🥴, but I wanted to share the full routine in compressed time.
.
Everyday from March to June or July 2020 this was my routine.  45 minutes of reps using 2.5kg ankle weights and dumbbells.  Sweat, hip hop and lots of pelvic shakes and thrusts = joy and yum.  I use a timer, and each set of reps is for 108 seconds, non-stop, for 45 minutes. I do timed stretches at the end and then I practice hip and thoracic isolations that come from belly dancing.  And all of it synced with the breath, creating a hypnotic effect that produces steadiness and rejuvenation
.
I love this little saucy routine so much, and found it so helpful for my mental health and also my Asana practice.  The strengthening of areas of the body used in our practice made me feel so much stronger and  lighter when On my mat.  Last year I made a  5 day program of this routine, (but more like the 1.0 version.  Version 2.0 to come) with 30 minute sessions.  I’m excited to finally share it!  It’s on my online studio for subscribers.  And you can join for 14 days, check it all out, and if it’s not for you we will give you a full refund. 

I LOVE to see us humans moving, shaking, breathing, sweating, giggling and feeling good and empowered.  I hope that where ever you are you can take a minute to shake it all out and have a giggle 😆
💙
Love 
Meghan 
.
Ps. I’ll be sharing some little snippets from the ‘Strength’ workbook I’ve created so that we can do some goal setting for the new moon today. Stay tuned!
.
.

node.text:
Our challenges are like obstacle courses that create the friction for us to evolve incrementally beyond our current state.  We have to feel like we are going backwards sometimes, or even just stuck in one spot, as these moments create the tension that’s sometimes necessary to catapult us into new territory. 
💙
 Remember all the greatness that has been grown in and from the muck of your adversities.  Focus on those growths in order to stay centered in the core of trusting the process you are in
💙
Love 
Meghan 
.
.
This song is from my new album and it’s called The Greatest Things. It’s about how the rough tough times can bring about the greatest things.  And how the roots of our greatest discomforts are oftener just to protect us from what we don’t yet know 
.
.
.
PS. I wrote a blog, (link in my bio) about the process of breathing.  There is a super cool video that illustrates it beautifully. 🥰😍😘
.
.
💙

node.text:
Hey!

Here is a short 15 minute meditation video that was part of a Breath Is Boss workshop I taught online.   

When we meet someone for the first time, and we meet them without imposing any assumptions about who we think they are, a more wide open experience arrives. Connections feel more real, relaxed and free. 

The same is true for how we meet and greet different aspects of ourselves. 

When we encounter different aspects of our inner environment with naked eyes and dissolved assumptions everything just feels better. We get softer, more landed, and there is a feeling of waking up a little more in the present moment.
 
This sweet little guided meditation is all about landing here and connecting to your body and breath as it is in this moment. We start by tuning into our sense of gravity, feeling it’s effects throughout flesh and bones. Then we open up to our breath and go on a little inner hike, exploring what’s up, dropping assumptions and relaxing into the present moment.  

Let me know how it went in the comments below! Any tiny insights or anything to share? 

Loving you, 
Meghan

PS. You can check out the full Breath Is Boss practice in the 6-Month Member’s Journey on my online studio! Head over to the link in my bio to explore more :)

#breathisboss
#loveeverymoment

Cause we all could use a healthy gasm to kick off the weekend right?
.
Here is a little quick, easy, healthy and delicious recipe I made yesterday! 
.
One Friday a month I am creating these little recipe inspirations for the members of my online studio, but this one was too juicy and yummy not to share here.  It turned out soooo well!  And it’s @grintini approved!
.
There are some ingredients here that you may not be able to find so easily, such as passion fruit and fresh rosella flower, but you can substitute based on flavor.
.
Rosella has a vibrant sour zing similar to cranberry. And passion fruits are sweet and tart, the cousin of citrus, so you can substitute orange and lemon!
.
I hope this inspires some fun invention of your own!
.
Please share with me your creations and comments!
.
Love!
Meghan

Sweet Humans! 

Welcome to your practice! 

Ebb And Flow is a slinky special class that I created for my new Meghan Currie Yoga Online Studio and I’m excited to share it with you here! 

This is a 30-minute simple, slow, but strong yoga flow to get you into your body and breath in a short period of time. Being present in each breath and each movement, can allow us to unfold deeper layers, bit by bit. Practicing like this can help us discover new places inside, places that were previously untapped.

I hope you can feel your presence amplified with this practice, and take that feeling with you throughout the day! 

Let me know your thoughts in the comments section below!

Click the link in my bio for the full length practice! 

See you on the mat!

node.title: 30-Minute Slow & Strong Yoga Flow: Ebb & Flow

node.text:
Just thank you 

It’s been less than a week since I released my first ever full length album and it’s already had over 12k streams!!! And I want to say a big huge THANK YOU! 

Thank you for all of your listens and shares and messages and support!  It means so much to me.  I could burst into tears and probably will tonight. 

Creating art in many forms, including the art of movement, is a passion I have spent my life exploring.  The urge to create for me is as strong as thirst.  Along side this, I am also woven with bundles of insecurity- each that arise powerfully when I share something Ive made.  Not gonna lie, these last months so many “old” insecurities have come up to the surface in a mighty way.  I’ve experienced so many shaky days spent questioning everything. 

These insecurities are a part of me that I have leaned I must embrace.  Embrace and work with.  I believe that these shaky parts that we are woven with, that seem to weaken us, might be the very thing that make us strong, when we embrace them. 

So thank you for being here. Even though this is a virtual space, I feel you.  And I appreciate every one of you.  Thanks for encouraging me to authentically express and create.  And I hope I can do the same for you! 

This song is called “We Breathe In”. It’s the first song on our album “Chasing Light”. The link to listen is in the link in my bio!

Loving you!!!
Meghan

Hey hi!
I wanted to share with you this song by my friends @sophiesofree and @r_a_i_o called Cunaq. You can find it in the Spotify link in my linktree if you click “What’s on my playlist”. I can’t get enough of it at the moment, her voice is so beautiful, it’s like a crystal singing bowl to me. 

I asked Sophie about the meaning, she said:

“It’s a song of praise and prayer to the Waters, which bring us purification and renewal. We shed our tears in order to see the world afresh, in joy and celebration. It’s Based on a traditional Peruvian water song” 
. 
I hope this song makes you flow, or purifies a little something something from your layers. 
.
I’m loving you from this moist chilly jungly cabin where I’m here wearing pants. Yes pants. And hoping you out there are taking gentle breaks from your devices to frolic around nonsensically making jokes with loved ones that are so not funny they are the funniest
. 
And, if you have seen any interesting, informative, controversial, moving, educational documentaries lately? Please do tell
. 
love and yum
Meghan 
.

node.text:
The light peeks out amplifying everything that’s been cleansed with the overwhelming smells of renewal.

There are times in our lives that feel like walking alone up an alligator inhabited shit stream on spiky stones in a lightening storm during an earthquake in the dark. Inner navigation sometimes leads us through these kinds of chasms and rational thought equates it to a mistake or wrong turn in the road. 

We can be wise and practice lots and do all the things and still get lost. And lost again. 

To get lost, feel confused, fall face first in a dung pile and lose your shoes can be a good sign. Maybe not a sign we can see at the time, but we all know what it’s like when the river turns clear, the sun peaks out from the clouds, we find our shoes and the lessons become crystallized in our blood.

But what to do when the storm is thick with no end in sight and the feels are terrorizing. 

One question I have been asking myself lately is: what does it look/feel like to approach this situation/relationship/shit storm/conflict- GRACEFULLY?

When I’m in the middle of a storm, asking this question does not suddenly clear the clouds, but it generates some tiny shifts in the way I realize my own resistance to the reality of my current situation. 

I’m nerding deep on the word GRACE this month as it’s the theme for studies in my online studio. 
What comes when I cozy up to this word is some kind of warm and soft, gentle but strong, sweet and beautiful presence. And when I try to apply this presence to my circumstance it teaches me allowance and gentle yielding to whatever the moment is washing over me. I remember with my body that grace is kindness to myself and the situation, whatever it may be. And when I really connect to the essence of the word grace, I’m taken to a beautiful core that resides in and through everything. 

Again, this does not clear the storm, nor does it mean that I’m suddenly in love with the situation or am taken over by feelings of peace and joy. But it imprints some wisdom somewhere and helps me let go of resistance, even just a little. 

I’m loving you from Bali and the bitches (aka-Lala, Dreamy, Soma) are sending sassy dirty-dog love too.

node.text:
When so many parts and pieces of life are vibrantly unpredictable and uncertain, reach to the things within that are beyond all the chatter. It’s that something bigger and it often takes getting wildly lost to find it
.
We are all woven and wired in ways that are guaranteed to be unique and so we each have our own personal way to plug into the space beyond the noise 
.
Space beyond the noise, still contains the noise. It’s the container. And it’s the place that maybe we can also find ourselves being more than capable of holding and accepting all contrasting parts.
.
It’s the birds eye view. The place that beams with the knowing that it’s okay. The rememberer of the how to take things as they come and the comforter that is cozy even amongst the perceived chaos. 
.
We don’t need to try to stay there forever. To be human is to dip in and out and to learn from the squiggly paths along the way. To grow as human Beings is to remember it’s who we are.

node.text:
Wherever life plants you, bloom with grace. 
- French Proverb
🌺 🌸 🌹 
.
I’ve been thinking soooo much about grace these last weeks, creating all new content based in the exploration of July’s theme, Grace, for my online studio
.
I’ve been looking at what it means to move, practice and to live gracefully
.
Wow it’s amazing how many facets to this word their are. So much depth and meaning. And this quote moved something in me that I’d forgotten
.
That even when faced with challenges, conflict, stress, and overall things not going in a direction that would seem optimal, to remember to bloom where I’m planted, no matter what the circumstance, takes me to another place of acceptance and understanding. 
So damn grateful for wise words that flick switches of perception and understanding, yay.
.
Loving you wherever you are 
❤️ 🌺 
Meghan

node.text:
Sometimes we have to fall out of balance to find balance. 

Sometimes the harder we fall, the better because those rocks at the bottom, when we hit them, don’t lie.  They knock the puzzle piece needed to see the lesson clearly, out of hiding. 
.
The Lessons in life that really stick rarely feel orgasmic and sometimes even ripping a bandaid off of a hairy spot can feel pleasurable in comparison. 
.
But the lessons like this, they stick stronger than superglue.  I’m learning a few of these at the moment.  It seems that any theme I create for my classes, I first must get spanked with.  It amazes me, often to tears of wft, how the lessons never stop. 

I’ve been frozen in some ways for the last month, but finally I feel some defrosting. This video is a slice of my yummy practice this am. Like coming home to the smell of curry on the stove yummy. It’s been a while since I’ve been able to self practice. Life had me occupied, stuck to a rocky bottom collecting old stones, but I’m happy to finally feel like I’m back. Needed to fall out of balance, um big time, to find a new way to stand.
.
How have you all been out there? Any spankings from hefty lessons lately? Missed you guys. Say hi pleaaaseeee 

Loving youuuu
Meghan

node.text:
Lovely Humans! 

When you think of creating a practice from a place of Moving From Love, do your  expectations change? What could it look like, feel like?  

I just released a deep and delicious workshop called “Move from Love” that delves into this topic and much more, and it’s included in the membership subscription on my online studio. It’s also a part of this month’s theme “Balance”, the fourth phase of the 6-Month Member’s Journey: Metamorphosis. I’m excited to share this workshop with you!

These recordings are taken from the Move from Love Online Intensive I taught during lockdown in 2020.  It comes with a Move From Love workbook that contains journal prompts to help you discover what you really want to create and a guide to creating Love Habits, that is, baby steps of action done for a few minutes a day to help you stay on track and create habits that light you up!

Move From Love is an 8-day workshop, consisting of 3, 3 hour classes of lecture, meditation and asana practices. The journal prompts can be completed before you start a class to open up the inner doorways to greater insight. 

Each session will focus on a certain topic to help us comprehend what we need to move from love.
 
- Session One - Love Word

An inquiry into the essence of love according to our assumption, what we have learned, and what it should seem.  

- Session Two - Life Energy Investments

A learning process about investing our energy to create rejuvenating, opening, and strengthening practices as well as a greater sense of grace and balance.
 

- Session Three - Self Acknowledgment

It's time to create the Love Habits by adding positive thoughts and actions to bring about  an uplifting outcome.

Click the linktr.ee in my bio and visit the Online Studio Membership page to find out more. 

Join this sweet self-discovery journey with me! I hope these practices will inspire and move you in the directions you want to grow. 

See you on the mat! 

Love,
Meghan

Hi, Wonderful Humans! 

I have created a little blog about goal-setting which is aligned with our monthly theme “Strength” for 6-month Member’s Journey: Metamorphosis. I would love to share a few insights about SMART goal setting as it is one of my favorite goal-setting structures. 

Goal-setting is a powerful exercise as it asks us to be brave in order to express what we value the most, and what we want to create. 

Read the full story by clicking the “New Blog Post” link in the Linktr.ee in my bio.
 
I’ve also created a workbook filled with journal prompts that will help you to go deeper into this topic and it’s included in the membership subscription on my online studio. Also included in the membership is a library of on-demand classes, live monthly classes, and other extra perks. 

To visit the Online Studio, click “Online Studio Membership” in the Linktr.ee in my bio. 

I hope this blog can inspire you to playfully daydream and map out what you want to create. 

Love you, 
Meghan
